    <fr:title text="Euler Lagrange Equations">Euler Lagrange Equations</fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
    <html:p>The Euler-Lagrange equations,
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\frac {\partial \mathcal {L}}{\partial  q_i}=\frac {d}{dt}\frac {\partial \mathcal {L}}{\partial \dot {q}_i}]]></fr:tex>
are a condition that is satisfied for a path that gives a stationary value for an equation of the form,
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[S=\int _{t_1}^{t_2}\mathcal {L}(q_1,\dot {q}_1,\dots ,q_n,\dot {q}_n,t)dt]]></fr:tex>
Where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q_i]]></fr:tex> is the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i]]></fr:tex>th coordinate parametrized by an independent variable <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[t]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\dot {q}_i]]></fr:tex> is the first derivative of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q]]></fr:tex> with respect to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[t]]></fr:tex>.
</html:p>
    <html:p>
      <html:strong>Proof</html:strong>
    </html:p>
    <html:p>For a full proof see Chapter 6 of Classical Mechanics by Taylor. In summary, one starts by considering variations from the correct path (the correct path gives a stationary point for S). After computing the variation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\partial  S]]></fr:tex>, integrating by parts, applying boundary conditions, and requiring <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\partial  S=0]]></fr:tex>, we find the condition of the Euler-Lagrange equations.</html:p>
  </fr:mainmatter>
